'''Pesto''' ({{IPA-it|ˈpesto|lang}}, {{IPA-lij|ˈpestu|lang}}), or to refer to the original dish '''pesto alla genovese''' ({{IPA-it|ˈpesto alla dʒenoˈveːse, -eːze}}), is a [[sauce]] originating in [[Genoa]], the capital city of [[Liguria]], [[Italy]].<ref name="itchefs">{{Cite web|title=Pesto Genovese: an Ageless Benchmark of Great Italian Cuisine|url=http://www.itchefs-gvci.com/?option=com_content&view=article&id=661&Itemid=1030|accessdate=11 October 2011}}</ref> It traditionally consists of crushed [[garlic]], European [[pine nut]]s, coarse salt, [[Basil|basil leaves]], and hard cheese such as [[Parmigiano-Reggiano]] (also known as Parmesan cheese) or [[Pecorino Sardo]] (cheese made from sheep's milk), all blended with [[olive oil]].<ref name="CMPM">{{Cite web|last=Campionato Mondiale Pesto al Mortaio|title=Pesto's official recipe|url=https://www.pestochampionship.it/en/about-pesto/official-championship-recipe.html|accessdate=10 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111018232331/http://pestochampionship.it/en/about-pesto/official-championship-recipe.html|archivedate=18 October 2011}}</ref>

== Etymology ==
The name is the past participle of the [[Genoese dialect|Genoese]] verb {{lang|lij|pestâ}} (Italian: {{lang|it|pestare}}), which means "to pound", "to crush", in reference to the original method of preparation: according to tradition, the ingredients are "crushed" or ground in a marble [[Mortar and pestle|mortar]] through a circular motion of a wooden [[Mortar and pestle|pestle]]. This same [[Latin]] root, through [[Old French]], also gave rise to the [[English language|English]] noun ''pestle''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.etymonline.com/word/pesto#etymonline_v_12782|title=pesto|work=Online Etymological Dictionary}}</ref>

Strictly speaking, ''pesto'' is a generic term for anything that is made by pounding; that is why the word is used for several pestos in Italy. Nonetheless, ''pesto alla genovese'' ("Genoese pesto") remains the most popular pesto in Italy and the rest of the world.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pronzati|first=Virgilio|date=2012|title=Come uno specialista di enogastronomia racconta la storia popolare Genovese|trans-title=How a food and wine specialist relates the Genoese folk history|chapter=Si fa presto a dire pesto|trans-chapter=It is one thing to say Pesto|url=http://www.acompagna.org/wit/chisiamo/iniziative/martedi/2011-2012/120320.pdf|location=Genoa|issue=I Martedì dell'associazione "A Compagna"|language=Italian|page=2 }}</ref>

== History ==
[[File:PastaWithPesto.JPG|thumb|[[Trenette]] with pesto.]]

Pesto is thought to have two predecessors in ancient times, going back as far as the [[Roman age]]. The [[Roman age|ancient Romans]] used to eat a similar paste called [[moretum]], which was made by crushing garlic, salt, cheese, herbs, olive oil and vinegar together.<ref name="itchefs"/><ref name="appendix">{{Cite web|title=Moretum – Appendix Vergiliana|url=http://www.virgil.org/appendix/moretum.htm|accessdate=19 January 2016}}</ref> The use of this paste in the Roman cuisine is mentioned in the ''[[Appendix Vergiliana#Moretum ("The Pesto")|Appendix Vergiliana]]'', an ancient collection of poems where the author dwells on the details about the preparation of ''moretum''.<ref name=appendix/> During the [[Middle Ages]], a popular sauce in the Genoan cuisine was ''agliata'', which was basically a mash of garlic and walnuts, as garlic was a staple in the nutrition of Ligurians, especially for the seafarers.<ref name="itchefs"/>

The introduction of basil, the main ingredient of modern pesto, occurred in more recent times and is first documented only in the mid-19th century, when gastronomist Giovanni Battista Ratto published his book ''La Cuciniera Genovese'' in 1863:<ref name="itchefs"/>

<blockquote>"''Take a clove of [[garlic]], [[basil]] or, when that is lacking, [[marjoram]] and [[parsley]], grated [[List of Dutch cheeses|Dutch]] and [[Parmigiano-Reggiano|Parmigiano]] cheese and mix them with [[pine nut]]s and crush it all together in a mortar with a little [[butter]] until reduced to a paste. Then dissolve it with good and abundant [[oil]]. [[Lasagne]] and [[Trofie]] are dressed with this mash, made more liquid by adding a little hot water without salt.
<ref>{{Cite book|last=Ratto|first=Giovanni Battista|title=La Cuciniera Genovese|publisher=Fratelli Pagano|date=1863|location=Genoa}}</ref></blockquote>

Although likely originating from and being domesticated in India,<ref name="McGee">{{Cite book|last=McGee|first=Harold|author-link=Harold McGee|title=[[On Food and Cooking]]: The Science and Lore of the Kitchen|date=2004|publisher=[[Charles Scribner's Sons|Scribner]]|location=[[New York, New York]]|isbn=978-0-684-80001-1|lccn=2004058999|oclc=56590708}}</ref> basil took the firmest root in the regions of [[Liguria]], Italy, and [[Provence]], France. It was abundant in this part of Italy, though only when in season, which is why marjoram and parsley are suggested as alternatives when basil is lacking.<ref name="itchefs"/> Ratto mentions Dutch cheese (''formaggio olandese'') instead of [[Pecorino Sardo]] since Northern European cheeses were actually common in Genoa at the time, thanks to the centuries-long commercial trades of the [[Republic of Genoa|maritime republic]].<ref name="itchefs"/>

This recipe for ''pesto alla genovese'' was often revised in the following years (a noted revision by Emanuele Rossi occurred in 1865, only a couple of years after Ratto's ''Cuciniera''),<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rossi|first=Emanuele|title=La vera cuciniera Genovese facile ed economica|date=1865|location=Genoa}}</ref> and it shortly became a staple in the Ligurian culinary tradition, with each family often featuring its own pesto recipe (with slight differences to the traditional ingredients).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zelfpestomaken.nl/|title=Zelf Pesto Maken}}</ref> This is the main reason why pesto recipes often differ from each other.

In 1944, ''[[The New York Times]]'' mentioned an imported canned pesto paste. In 1946, ''[[Sunset (magazine)|Sunset]]'' magazine published a pesto recipe by [[Angelo Pellegrini]]. Pesto did not become popular in North America until the 1980s and 1990s.<ref name="sunsetApril2008">{{Cite news|last=Traverso|first=Amy|title=Pesto's Premiere|newspaper=Sunset|page=116|date=April 2008|url=https://www.sunset.com/sunset/food/article/0,20633,1717438,00.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513052652/http://www.sunset.com/sunset/food/article/0,20633,1717438,00.html|archivedate=13 May 2008|accessdate=22 July 2008}}</ref>

== Ingredients and preparation ==
Pesto is traditionally prepared in a marble mortar with a wooden pestle. First, garlic and pine nuts are placed in the mortar and reduced to a cream,<ref name=CMPM/> and then the washed and dried basil leaves are added with coarse salt and ground to a creamy consistency. Only then is a mix of Parmigiano-Reggiano and Pecorino added. To help incorporate the cheese a little extra-virgin olive oil is added. In a tight jar (or simply in an air-tight plastic container), covered by a layer of extra-virgin olive oil, pesto can last in the refrigerator up to a week, and can be frozen for later use.<ref name="Consorzio del pesto Genovese recipe">{{Cite web|work=mangiareinliguria.it|url=http://www.mangiareinliguria.it/consorziopestogenovese/pestogenovese.php|title=Consorzio del pesto Genovese recipe|access-date=21 February 2008}}</ref>

